pr_review_body:
@Priyansh19077 there may be other opinions from other maintainers, but I would not be comfortable with approving a fix for this issue that is based on playing around with `sys.setrecursionlimit`. I could possibly consider a PR that adds a way to set `sys.setrecursionlimit` for our command line tools (e.g. rdfpipe).

Further, this PR does not add a tests for the issue, so there is little to salvage. 

Happy to review once tests are in place with a solution not based on `sys.setrecursionlimit`.

I really like the organizational changes here. I think these are great changes that make specifying asset dependencies much more understandable.

As far as the updating the source asset code example, what feels like it could be improved about the example? I personally would make some small edits to the code to make it more readable:
```
from dagster import AssetGroup, AssetKey, Output, SourceAsset, asset, repository


@asset
def simple_asset():
    return 5


@asset
def double_asset(simple_asset):
    return simple_asset * 2

@repository
def upstream_repo():
    return [AssetGroup(assets=[simple_asset, transform_asset])]


my_source_asset = SourceAsset(key=AssetKey("simple_asset"))

@asset
def add_one_asset(simple_asset):
    return simple_asset + 1

@repository
def downstream_repo():
    return [AssetGroup(assets=[add_one_asset], source_assets=[my_source_asset])]
```
If it's helpful, I could update the example with any changes you think would be good.

I left some other comments inline (I know some are preexisting issues, but I think it's worth addressing them now)

Thanks @FabianHofmann for the time for the review and comments.
@enricogiglio I added some comments for moving towards the final implementation, in agreement to the discussion had with fabian :)
Let's coordinate, also in agreement with the holidays (please, take them :) )

@Corvince This is great! so compact and elegant. To backbrief this adds the function batch_run while keeping the old classes so users now have an alternative. Should we add a deprecation warning to other classes? 

The only item of note was in tesst it wasn't using unittests like the other test modules, so I had to add some lines to run locally

One potential item was requires use of freeze_support for Windows OS

@sfdcale : Looks very close to me. In either this PR or another, can you please add documentation? 

It looks like the docs would go in "data.rst".

If you can get to this Monday or Tuesday there is a good chance it can go in the next CCI release.

I propose to converge with #324 to co-author something to:
- avoid duplicated reviews and stuffs;
- design something standardized.

One additional item to note is that there is some usable whitespace in the mobile cards between the footer & the text. I think maybe an 8px vertical padding on the activity type (the icon & "watch/read/etc" bit) in mobile might give some good spacing between the thumbnail and the activity and the title.

Of course, items with small descriptions or no description are doomed to have some whitespace there, but this example is truncated. Maybe even using the standard font size could make use of the available space naturally without needing.

I quickly tried it out in devtools and a combination of these changes feel to maximize the use of available whitespace (but would need some testing, maybe tweaking for desktop vs mobile). 

```
.metadata-info {
    margin: 8px 0; // This won't look right on desktop though
}

.text {
    /* other .text styles */
    font-size: 16px;
}
```

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6356129/135141332-0461921c-de2a-45b0-b8ea-806e98428219.png)

@cojenco I'm not sure how this PR addresses #653 or #134.  The current behavior is that if the user does **not** pass an explicit project, the constructor falls back to inferring the project from the credentials / environment, but if the user passes an **explicit** `None` for the project, the constructor remembers that fact, preventing its accidental use when calling `Client.create_bucket` or `Client.list_buckets`.  For the rationale, see https://github.com/googleapis/google-cloud-python/issues/4239.

The two referenced bugs are both about failures to find the project ID in the credentials inferred from the environment, and thus won't be affected by this change at all.

Removing the client-side validation from `Client.create_bucket` / `Client.list_buckets` shouldn't hurt anything:  the [`buckets.insert`](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/buckets/insert) and [`buckets.list`](https://cloud.google.com/storage/docs/json_api/v1/buckets/list) APIs will both raise exceptions if `project` is not passed.

@Irving-cl  this is a great enhancement. Thank you 👍 👍 

I added some suggestion below on having `ItemType` be a nested type defined by `IteratorType`. I also like the suggestion to include `mItem` in the `ItemPtrIterator`. Thoughts?

Thanks.
